rawContent:
HEALTHY TIP OF THE DAY

Elderberries are the fruit of the Sambucus tree. The most common type is the Sambucus nigra. They contain high levels of anti-oxidants, flavonoids, vitamin A, vitamin C, potassium, calcium, folate, iron and fiber. (Read till the end for syrup recipe)

Elderberries support heart health, improve antioxidant status, and have a variety of anti-cancer, anti-diabetes, and anti-inflammatory effects.

ELDERBERRIES SYRUP (shared by a friend)
1/2 cup fresh dried blue or black elderberries
3 cups of filtered water (cold)
3/4 cup raw honey
Place berries and water in a saucepan. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat and simmer for 30 minutes. Cover pot to reduce evaporation.
Smash berries to release the remaining juice. You can use a potato masher. Strain the mixture and discard the smashed berries.
Allow the strained mixture to cool and stir in honey while the mixture is still slightly warm. The raw honey is added at the end because heating it too much will destroy its natural healthful properties.
Syrup will last 2-3 months in the refrigerator.
Take one teaspoon per day for general health and wellness and to help prevent sickness or a teaspoon a day when you are sick. It’s great for helping to fight the viral illnesses.
